{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16801"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16801"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9492"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5162"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman with epilepsy presents for medication review. She has been experiencing breakthrough seizures on carbamazepine and reports feeling constantly drowsy. Her neurologist recommends switching to lamotrigine due to its different mechanism of action and more favourable side effect profile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of lamotrigine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits glutamate synthesis","Antagonises glutamate receptors","Blocks calcium channels","Enhances GABA neurotransmission","Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of lamotrigine is \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking voltage-gated sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E in neurons. This stabilises neuronal membranes and prevents excessive firing, ultimately reducing the release of excitatory neurotransmitters, particularly glutamate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits glutamate synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: lamotrigine reduces glutamate release through sodium channel blockade but does not affect its synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: whilst lamotrigine does reduce glutamate release, it does not directly block its receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E: although lamotrigine may have minor effects on calcium channels, this is not its primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances GABA neurotransmission\u003C/strong\u003E: while some anticonvulsants work through this mechanism, lamotrigine does not significantly affect GABA transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium channel blocking effect leads to reduced neuronal excitability and decreased release of excitatory neurotransmitters, making it effective in both epilepsy and bipolar disorder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lamotrigine acts primarily by blocking voltage-gated sodium channels in neurons, reducing glutamate release.","Lamotrigine is effective in treating both epilepsy and bipolar disorder.","Unlike many antiepileptic medications, lamotrigine has minimal sedating effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16801"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:06:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T12:02:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9492"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA